{"cursor":"18107","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox scientist |name = Lynn Margulis |image = Lynn_Margulis.jpg |image_size\n= |caption = |birth_date = |birth_place = Chicago, Illinois, U.S. |death_date =\n|death_place = Amherst, Massachusetts, U.S. |residence = |nationality = American\n|field = Biology |work_institutions = |alma_mater = |known_for =\nEndosymbiotic theory |prizes = William Procter Prize for Scientific Achievement\n}} 'Lynn Margulis' (born 'Lynn Alexander'; March 5,\n1938 â November 22, 2011) was an American biologist and\nUniversity Professor in the Department of Geosciences at the University of\nMassachusetts Amherst. [http://www.geo.umass.edu/faculty/margulis Lynn Margulis\nbiography at U. Mass.] (Accessed July 15, 2006) She is best known for her\ntheory on the origin of eukaryotic organelles, and her contributions to the\nendosymbiotic theory, which is now generally accepted for how certain organelles\nwere formed. She showed that animals, plants, and fungi all originated from\nprotists. She is also associated with the Gaia hypothesis, based on an idea\ndeveloped by the English environmental scientist James Lovelock.\n","linknr":911,"url":"Lynn_Margulis","recorded":1362509322,"links":68,"instances":["evolutionary_biology","company"],"pdf":["http://www1.biogema.de/WEK/312-Margulis-final.pdf"],"categories":["1938 births","2011 deaths","Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences","American biologists","Symbiosis","National Medal of Science laureates","Women biologists","American scientists","University of Massachusetts Amherst faculty","Boston University faculty","University of Chicago alumni","University of Wisconsin–Madison alumni","University of California, Berkeley alumni"],"headings":["Research","Professional recognition","Personal background","Death","Select publications and bibliography","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/08/Lynn_Margulis.jpg/220